
Day 16: Jenkins CronJob, Poll SCM, and Webhooks

1. CronJob

A CronJob is used to schedule a build to run at specific times automatically.
	• Syntax: * * * * * (Five stars representing time units).
	• Note: Use Server Time. Type date in your Linux terminal to see the current server time.
	• Time Units:
		1. Minute: (0-59)
		2. Hour: (0-23)
		3. Date: (1-31)
		4. Month: (1-12)
		5. Day: (0-6, where 0 is Sunday)
	Example: To schedule a build for 11:05 on August 9th (if that day is a Friday/Day 5), the syntax would be: 5 11 8 9 5
Steps to Create a CronJob:
	1. Create a CI Job.
	2. Go to Build Triggers.
	3. Select Build Periodically.
	4. Paste your Cron Syntax.
	5. Save.
	• Limitation: A CronJob will run automatically at the scheduled time regardless of whether the source code has actually changed.

2. Poll SCM

Builds will run only when code changes are detected in the Source Code Management (SCM) system.
	• How it works: Jenkins "polls" (checks) the repository at a scheduled interval. If it sees a new commit, it triggers a build.
	• Limitation: There is still a delay. If a developer pushes code at 7:00 AM but the Poll SCM is scheduled for 9:00 AM, the build won't start for two hours, leading to wasted time.
Steps to Create Poll SCM:
	1. Create a CI Job.
	2. Go to Build Triggers.
	3. Select Poll SCM.
	4. Paste the Cron Syntax (defining how often Jenkins should check for changes).
	5. Save.

3. Webhooks
A Webhook is the most efficient method. It triggers a build instantly as soon as code is committed (pushed) to GitHub.
Step 1: Settings on GitHub
	1. Go to your GitHub Repository -> Settings -> Webhooks.
	2. Click Add webhook.
	3. Payload URL: http://[Jenkins-IP]:8080/github-webhook/
	4. Content type: application/json
	5. Click Add webhook.
Step 2: Steps on Jenkins
	1. Go to your Jenkins Dashboard -> Create CI Job.
	2. Go to Build Triggers.
	3. Select GitHub hook trigger for GITScm polling.
	4. Save.

4. Remote Triggering

This allows you to trigger a build from outside the Jenkins UI (e.g., using a URL in a browser or a script).
	1. Create Job -> Build Triggers -> Trigger builds remotely.
	2. Set an Authentication Token (e.g., raham).
	3. Save.
	4. To trigger the build, use this URL format:
http://[IP]:8080/job/[Job-Name]/build?token=[Token-Name]
(Example: http://35.180.225.237:8080/job/job-1/build?token=raham)

5. Throttle Builds
Used to restrict the number of builds allowed within a specific time interval to prevent server overload.
	• Steps:
		1. Create/Configure Job.
		2. Select Throttle builds.
		3. Set Number of builds (e.g., 3).
		4. Set Time period (e.g., hours).
		5. Save.
	• Example: Setting 3 builds per hour ensures that even if 20 commits are made, Jenkins will only process them at a rate of approximately one build every 20 minutes.
